Mrs Walton says she witnessed the strong bond between the her son and Mr Lancaster on Monday afternoon.

'Zac is quite shy and doesn't warm up to anyone easily but for some reason, I don't know what it was, he connected with Jono,' she said.

'Maybe it's because Jono is such a friendly and caring person who isn't judgemental.'

Just recently, Mrs Walton pleaded with the South Australian Government after they announced they were going to take away the highly-trained nurse who helps look after her son Zackary one day a week.

The mother of five whose two-year-old son could die at any moment without round the clock care has told how she 'cried with happiness' after her campaign to stop her son's help being cut was successful. 

Zackary also has a tracheostomy, which means his airway is compromised and could be obstructed at any moment.

